column13: Sample_extract_protocol_ch1
column15: Sample_data_processing
column40: processed data files format and content
column49: We selected the highest quality barcodes for each case based on two criteria

column13: Nuclei were extracted from frozen tissues following the “Frakenstein” protocol developed by Luciano Martelotto, Ph.D., Melbourne, Centre for Cancer Research, Victorian Comprehensive Cancer Centre, and available from 10X Genomics, For fresh tissues, 10.2 μL of live cells, at a concentration of 1700 live-cells/μL,were loaded into the10X Chromium Single Cell capture chip. For frozen tissues, ~15,000 nuclei were loaded per capture. Single-cell/nucleus capture, reverse transcription, cell lysis, and library preparation were performed per manufacturer’s protocol. Sequencing was performed on an Illumina NovaSeq using apaired-end 100bp protocol.
column15: The CellRanger ATAC software (version 1.1.0) was used for read alignment, deduplication, and identifying transposase cut sites.
column40: Matrix file (mtx) includes sparse matrix of read counts, unique cell barcode files (tsv), and feature file (tsv)
